const SEARCH_INDEX = [{"url": "index.html#the-decentralizedheadless-cms-protocol", "pageTitle": "Introduction", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "The DecentralizedHeadless CMS Protocol", "text": "Morse shifts content permission management on-chain  publication identity, write permissions, and revision history all live in Sui Move smart contracts, while content payloads are stored in Walrus decentralized storage. Quick Start Core Concepts"}, {"url": "index.html#what-is-morse", "pageTitle": "Introduction", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "What is Morse?", "text": "Morse is a decentralized, headless content management system (dCMS) protocol. Traditional headless CMSs  Strapi, Ghost, Contentful  store content in centralized databases controlled by a single vendor. Morse shifts the control plane on-chain. The protocol separates three concerns clearly: Permission management  who can create, update, and publish  lives in Sui Move smart contracts. Storage  content payloads and assets  lives in Walrus decentralized storage. Delivery  fast reads and search  is served by off-chain indexers and APIs that anyone can run. 💡 Agent-first by design Morse is designed for autonomous development workflows. A coding agent can define content structures, provision publications, publish content, and operate the entire backend via CLI or SDK  without waiting for centralized provisioning."}, {"url": "index.html#system-architecture", "pageTitle": "Introduction", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "System Architecture", "text": "Morse is composed of five layers. Only the contracts are the source of truth; all other layers are replaceable. Control ⛓ Sui Blockchain  Publication Registry Collections Entries &amp; Revisions OwnerCap / PublisherCap ↕ Storage 🦭 Walrus  Blob Storage Quilt Storage ↕ Encryption 🔏 Seal  Publisher Policy Subscription Policy ↕ Read 📡 Indexer  Content API ↕ Develop 📦 TypeScript SDK 💻 CLI"}, {"url": "index.html#key-features", "pageTitle": "Introduction", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Key Features", "text": "🏛 On-chain Permission Management Publication identity, write permissions, and state transitions are enforced by Move smart contracts  transparent and auditable. 🦭 Walrus Storage Content payloads and assets live in Walrus decentralized storage. Contracts store verifiable references, not bytes. 🔐 Capability-Based Auth OwnerCap and PublisherCap separate permission management from publishing. Revocation is instant and denylist-based. 📜 Immutable Revisions Every content change is an appended revision. Draft and public heads enable editorial workflows without losing history. 🔓 Access Policies Public, publisher-gated, and subscription access policies control payload retrieval via Seal encryption. 🔌 Open Protocol Anyone can build integrations directly on contracts. Off-chain services are optional ergonomics, not gatekeepers."}, {"url": "index.html#component-status", "pageTitle": "Introduction", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Component Status", "text": "Component Status Description Move Contracts Active Publication, collection, entry, and revision management. Deployed on Sui Testnet. TypeScript SDK In Progress Wraps Sui and Walrus interactions for application developers. CLI In Progress Terminal tool for managing publications, collections, and entries. Indexer Planned Listens to on-chain events and builds read-optimized state. Content API Planned REST API for querying publications, collections, and entries. Admin DApp Planned Web UI for editors and publication owners."}, {"url": "index.html#why-morse", "pageTitle": "Introduction", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Why Morse?", "text": "Traditional headless CMSs create several long-term constraints: Trust concentration  one vendor backend controls all identity and data. Weak portability  publication identity and permissions don't travel with you. Opaque history  change and authorization history is hidden inside a closed system. Vendor lock-in  migrating requires re-building your backend from scratch. Morse solves these while keeping the ergonomics of headless CMS architecture. Publication identity is canonical on-chain. Write permissions are capability-based and verifiable. Every revision is auditable. And any team can integrate directly with the contracts, bypassing any specific service provider."}, {"url": "index.html#next-steps", "pageTitle": "Introduction", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Next Steps", "text": "⚡ Quick Start Deploy contracts and create your first publication in minutes. 📐 Core Concepts Understand the Publication → Collection → Entry model. 📰 Publications Deep dive into the top-level container and slug system. ⛓ Contract Reference Events, error codes, and full Move module reference."}, {"url": "quick-start.html#quick-start", "pageTitle": "Quick Start", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Quick Start", "text": "Get Morse running on testnet in under 10 minutes. You will deploy the contracts, create your first publication, add a collection, and publish your first content entry."}, {"url": "quick-start.html#prerequisites", "pageTitle": "Quick Start", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Prerequisites", "text": "Make sure you have the following installed before proceeding: Tool Version Purpose Sui CLI Latest Build and deploy Move contracts Bun v1.2+ Runtime for CLI and SDK Task v3+ Task runner for contract workflows You will also need a funded Sui testnet wallet . Use sui client faucet to get test SUI tokens."}, {"url": "quick-start.html#1-clone-the-repository", "pageTitle": "Quick Start", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "1. Clone the Repository", "text": "bash Copy git clone https://github.com/TheDivic/morse-dcms.git cd morse-dcms/morse-contracts"}, {"url": "quick-start.html#2-build-amp-test-contracts", "pageTitle": "Quick Start", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "2. Build &amp; Test Contracts", "text": "Ensure you are on the Sui testnet environment before building. The Move.toml is configured to target testnet by default. bash Copy # Build the Move package task build # Run the full test suite task test # Run a single test by name sui move test test_new_publication"}, {"url": "quick-start.html#3-deploy-to-testnet", "pageTitle": "Quick Start", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "3. Deploy to Testnet", "text": "⚠️ Funded wallet required Your active Sui wallet must have testnet SUI tokens. Run sui client faucet to request tokens from the faucet. bash Copy task publish After publishing, the package address and shared object IDs are saved to Published.toml . You will need the PublicationRegistry object ID for subsequent transactions."}, {"url": "quick-start.html#local-development-optional", "pageTitle": "Quick Start", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Local Development (Optional)", "text": "If you want to iterate without touching testnet, use the localnet workflow: bash Copy # Terminal 1  keep running task localnet # Terminal 2  wait ~60s for coins to arrive task faucet # Publish ephemerally (does not update Published.toml) task publish:local # Clean up and switch back to testnet task clean task switch:testnet ℹ️ Chain ID mismatch? Each fresh localnet gets a new chain ID. If publish:local fails with a chain-id mismatch, run task clean first to remove the stale Pub.local.toml ."}, {"url": "quick-start.html#4-create-your-first-publication", "pageTitle": "Quick Start", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "4. Create Your First Publication", "text": "Once deployed, interact with the contracts using Programmable Transaction Blocks (PTBs) via the Sui CLI. The new_publication function returns three objects  share the publication and transfer the capabilities in the same PTB. move Copy // In your PTB (Programmable Transaction Block): // Step 1  create publication, returns (Publication, OwnerCap, PublisherCap) let (publication, owner_cap, publisher_cap) = publication:: new_publication ( & mut registry, ctx, b \"My Blog\" .to_string(), b \"my-blog\" .to_string(), // unique slug: lowercase, alphanumeric, hyphens ); // Step 2  share the publication so publishers can write to it publication:: share_publication (publication); // Step 3  transfer caps to your wallet transfer:: transfer (owner_cap, sender); transfer:: transfer (publisher_cap, sender);"}, {"url": "quick-start.html#5-add-a-collection", "pageTitle": "Quick Start", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "5. Add a Collection", "text": "Choose a storage mode based on your content type. Use Blob mode for articles and posts; Quilt mode for site pages and structured configs. move Copy // storage_mode: 0 = blob, 1 = quilt publication:: create_collection ( & mut publication, &publisher_cap, b \"articles\" .to_string(), 0 , // STORAGE_MODE_BLOB ctx, );"}, {"url": "quick-start.html#6-publish-your-first-entry", "pageTitle": "Quick Start", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "6. Publish Your First Entry", "text": "Upload your content to Walrus first to get a Blob object, then register it on-chain: move Copy // blob is a Walrus Blob object (must be deletable) let entry_id = publication:: add_entry_to_collection ( & mut publication, &publisher_cap, b \"articles\" .to_string(), b \"Welcome Post\" .to_string(), // entry name &blob, // Walrus Blob object option:: none (), // no QuiltPatchId for blob mode b \"application/json\" .to_string(), // MIME content type false , // not encrypted entry:: access_policy_public (), // ACCESS_PUBLIC = 0 option:: none (), // no Seal identity ctx, ); // entry_id is the stable monotonic ID assigned (0, 1, 2, ...) ✅ You're live on-chain The entry is now registered. Its public_head points to revision 0, making it immediately readable. Any indexer watching the chain will pick it up."}, {"url": "quick-start.html#next-steps", "pageTitle": "Quick Start", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Next Steps", "text": "📐 Core Concepts Understand the data model and how all pieces fit together. 📰 Publications Learn about the slug system, capabilities, and publication lifecycle. 🔐 Access Control Issue publisher caps, revoke access, and set up Seal encryption."}, {"url": "core-concepts.html#core-concepts", "pageTitle": "Core Concepts", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Core Concepts", "text": "Understand the fundamental building blocks of the Morse protocol  the data model, authorization system, storage strategy, and how on-chain and off-chain components interact."}, {"url": "core-concepts.html#the-data-model", "pageTitle": "Core Concepts", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "The Data Model", "text": "Morse organizes content in a four-level hierarchy. Each level is stored on-chain and has a clear responsibility: Level 1 📰 Publication → e.g. my-blog  a brand-level content domain ↓ Level 2 🗂 Collection → e.g. articles , site-pages  content lanes ↓ Level 3 📝 Entry → e.g. welcome-post  a single content unit ↓ Level 4 📜 Revision → immutable snapshot  blob reference + metadata Editors operate mostly at the Entry / Revision level. Owners operate mostly at the Publication / Authorization level."}, {"url": "core-concepts.html#publications", "pageTitle": "Core Concepts", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Publications", "text": "A Publication is the top-level shared object in Morse. It is the permission management boundary for all content under a brand or domain. Identified by an immutable slug (e.g. my-blog ) registered in the global PublicationRegistry . Slug uniqueness is enforced globally  no two active publications can share a slug. Contains a map of named collections. Tracks a denylist of revoked publisher caps. Publications use key ability only (no store )  sharing and transfer are gated through module functions, not arbitrary object movement."}, {"url": "core-concepts.html#collections", "pageTitle": "Core Concepts", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Collections", "text": "A Collection is a named content lane inside a publication. Its storage mode is immutable after creation and determines how content references are stored: Mode Value Best for Blob reference type Blob 0 Growing collections  articles, posts, media libraries. Content changes independently. Blob(ID)  Sui object ID of a standalone Walrus Blob Quilt 1 Small, stable collections  site pages, config-like structured documents. QuiltPatch(vector&lt;u8&gt;)  37-byte patch identifier within a shared quilt Entries inside a collection are keyed by a monotonic entry_id ( u64 ). IDs are stable  they never get renumbered after deletions (gaps are expected)."}, {"url": "core-concepts.html#entries-amp-revisions", "pageTitle": "Core Concepts", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Entries &amp; Revisions", "text": "An Entry is a single content unit in a collection. It holds an immutable, append-only revision vector ."}, {"url": "core-concepts.html#the-dual-head-model", "pageTitle": "Core Concepts", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "The Dual-Head Model", "text": "Each entry maintains two head pointers: draft_head  points to the latest draft revision. Editors can iterate here without affecting what readers see. public_head  points to the currently published revision. Readers and indexers use this. This dual-head model enables real editorial workflows: drafts can evolve privately while production clients serve stable published content."}, {"url": "core-concepts.html#what-a-revision-contains", "pageTitle": "Core Concepts", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "What a Revision Contains", "text": "Each EntryRevision is immutable once appended. It stores: blob_ref  either a Blob(ID) or QuiltPatch(bytes) pointing to the Walrus payload. content_type  MIME type string (e.g. application/json , text/markdown ). encrypted  whether the Walrus payload is Seal-encrypted. access_policy  0 (public), 1 (publisher), or 2 (subscription). seal_id  Seal identity for encrypted revisions (required when encrypted = true ). author  address of the transaction sender who created this revision."}, {"url": "core-concepts.html#capability-based-authorization", "pageTitle": "Core Concepts", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Capability-Based Authorization", "text": "Morse uses two capabilities to separate publication permission management from day-to-day publishing: 👑 OwnerCap One per publication. Required to issue or revoke PublisherCaps, delete the publication, and transfer ownership. Transferable by design  ownership can be sold or delegated. ✍️ PublisherCap Many per publication. Required for all write operations. Bound to a specific holder address  a moved or shared cap object cannot be used by unapproved addresses."}, {"url": "core-concepts.html#revocation-denylist", "pageTitle": "Core Concepts", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Revocation Denylist", "text": "Revocation is denylist-based , not allowlist-based. This is an important design choice: Issuing a cap has zero table writes  caps are valid by construction. Only revocations write to the revoked_publisher_caps table. This optimizes for the common case (no revocations) and makes issuing caps cheap. Safe because PublisherCap has no store ability and no external constructor  caps cannot be fabricated outside the module. 💡 Revocation is immediate Once a PublisherCap ID is added to the denylist, all future writes using that cap will be rejected  without modifying historical content state."}, {"url": "core-concepts.html#walrus-storage", "pageTitle": "Core Concepts", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Walrus Storage", "text": "Walrus is a decentralized blob storage protocol. Morse uses it to store the actual content payloads and assets, keeping large bytes off-chain while preserving on-chain verifiable references. Walrus is format-agnostic  it stores binary blobs. Morse can support JSON, Markdown, images, video, or any custom schema. Contracts store references to blobs ( blob_id or QuiltPatchId ), not the payload bytes themselves. Blobs must be deletable  Morse enforces this by requiring the actual &Blob object (not just an ID) in production write paths."}, {"url": "core-concepts.html#quiltpatchid-format", "pageTitle": "Core Concepts", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "QuiltPatchId Format", "text": "For Quilt mode collections, each revision stores a 37-byte compact identifier: QuiltPatchId = quilt_blob_id (32 bytes) + version ( 1 byte ) + start_index ( 2 bytes) + end_index ( 2 bytes)"}, {"url": "core-concepts.html#access-control-amp-seal", "pageTitle": "Core Concepts", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Access Control &amp; Seal", "text": "Morse supports three access policies on content revisions: Policy Constant Description Public 0 Unencrypted. Anyone can read the Walrus payload directly. Publisher 1 Encrypted via Seal. Only active publishers of this publication can decrypt. Subscription 2 Reserved. Planned for subscription-gated content with Seal policies. Seal is MystenLabs' access control system for encrypted Walrus content. The seal_approve_publisher entry function in the contracts validates that a caller holds an active, non-revoked PublisherCap before approving decryption."}, {"url": "core-concepts.html#off-chain-services", "pageTitle": "Core Concepts", "section": "Getting Started", "heading": "Off-Chain Services", "text": "The blockchain is the canonical source of truth, but off-chain services improve the developer experience: Indexer  listens to on-chain events and builds a read-optimized state database. Content API  serves fast queries for listings, slug resolution, and payload references. SDK  TypeScript package that wraps Sui/Walrus/Seal interactions for app developers. CLI  command-line tool for scripted automation, CI, and agent-native workflows. 🔌 Open protocol guarantee Off-chain services are replaceable . Any team can run their own indexer, API, or integrate directly with the contracts via the SDK. Protocol access is never gated by a single service provider."}, {"url": "publications.html#publications", "pageTitle": "Publications", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Publications", "text": "A publication is the top-level permission management and identity boundary for a content domain in Morse. Everything  collections, entries, permissions  lives inside a publication."}, {"url": "publications.html#what-is-a-publication", "pageTitle": "Publications", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "What is a Publication?", "text": "A Publication is a shared Sui object that acts as the root container for one content brand or site. It bundles: A human-readable name (display label) An immutable, globally unique slug (canonical URL key) A collection map holding all named content lanes A revocation denylist for publisher capabilities Move Copy public struct Publication has key { id: UID , name: String , slug: String , collections: VecMap &lt; String , Collection &gt;, revoked_publisher_caps: Table &lt; ID , bool &gt;, } key only, no store. The Publication type has key ability but no store . Sharing and transfer are gated through this module's own functions, enforced by the Sui type system. You cannot wrap or freely transfer a publication  you must call share_publication ."}, {"url": "publications.html#the-slug-system", "pageTitle": "Publications", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "The Slug System", "text": "Every publication is identified by a slug  a short, lowercase string that becomes its canonical identifier across the protocol. Slugs are enforced to be globally unique by the PublicationRegistry ."}, {"url": "publications.html#slug-rules", "pageTitle": "Publications", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Slug Rules", "text": "Rule Constraint Characters Lowercase letters a–z , digits 0–9 , hyphens - Length 1 to 64 characters Edge hyphens Cannot start or end with - Uniqueness Must be globally unique while the publication is active Immutability Cannot be changed after publication creation Examples Copy // valid slugs \"my-blog\" \"acme-corp\" \"docs2025\" // invalid slugs \"-leading-hyphen\" // ESlugInvalidEdgeHyphen \"trailing-hyphen-\" // ESlugInvalidEdgeHyphen \"UPPERCASE\" // ESlugInvalidChar \"spaces not allowed\" // ESlugInvalidChar \"\" // ESlugEmpty"}, {"url": "publications.html#slug-reuse-after-deletion", "pageTitle": "Publications", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Slug Reuse After Deletion", "text": "When a publication is deleted, its slug is released from the registry and becomes available again. This is a deliberate tradeoff  it gives publishers flexibility to re-register slugs  but teams should be aware that a released slug can be re-claimed by anyone. Manage this at the product layer if slug continuity is critical."}, {"url": "publications.html#publicationregistry", "pageTitle": "Publications", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "PublicationRegistry", "text": "The PublicationRegistry is a shared singleton object created once in the package init function. It maintains a global Table&lt;String, ID&gt; mapping slugs to publication IDs, enforcing uniqueness across all publications. Move Copy public struct PublicationRegistry has key { id: UID , slugs: Table &lt; String , ID &gt;, } // Look up a slug public fun contains_slug (registry: & PublicationRegistry , slug: String ): bool // Resolve slug → publication ID public fun get_publication_id_by_slug (registry: & PublicationRegistry , slug: String ): & ID The registry is a mandatory argument to new_publication . You cannot create a publication without passing the shared registry object."}, {"url": "publications.html#creating-a-publication", "pageTitle": "Publications", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Creating a Publication", "text": "Publication creation follows the pure-function pattern : new_publication returns objects without performing any transfers. The caller decides what to do with them in a Programmable Transaction Block (PTB). Move Copy public fun new_publication ( registry: & mut PublicationRegistry , ctx: & mut TxContext , name: String , slug: String , ): ( Publication , OwnerCap , PublisherCap ) // After creation, share the publication so others can interact with it public fun share_publication (publication: Publication ) new_publication returns three objects in a tuple: Publication  the shared content container OwnerCap  admin authority (keep with the owner wallet) PublisherCap  initial write authority (bound to the transaction sender) PTB pattern. In a single Programmable Transaction Block, call new_publication to get the three objects, transfer the caps to the appropriate wallets, and call share_publication to make the publication accessible. The split between creation and sharing is intentional  it keeps construction pure and lets the caller compose freely."}, {"url": "publications.html#deleting-a-publication", "pageTitle": "Publications", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Deleting a Publication", "text": "Publications can be deleted, but only when all collections have been removed first . Attempting to delete a publication with remaining collections aborts with an error. Move Copy public fun delete_publication ( registry: & mut PublicationRegistry , publication: Publication , owner_cap: OwnerCap , ) On deletion: The OwnerCap is consumed and its UID deleted The slug is removed from the registry (emits SlugReleased ) The revocation denylist is dropped (safe because bool has drop ) The publication UID is deleted A PublicationDeleted event is emitted Collections must be empty before deletion. The VecMap of collections will abort on destroy_empty if any collections remain. Remove all collections (and their entries) before calling delete_publication ."}, {"url": "publications.html#ownership-transfer", "pageTitle": "Publications", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Ownership Transfer", "text": "Publication ownership can be transferred by transferring the OwnerCap to a new address. Since OwnerCap has only the key ability, transfer is handled by the module: Move Copy public fun transfer_owner_cap (owner_cap: OwnerCap , recipient: address ) The recipient immediately gains full admin authority  the ability to issue/revoke publisher caps and delete the publication. Existing publisher caps remain valid until individually revoked."}, {"url": "publications.html#events", "pageTitle": "Publications", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Events", "text": "The publications module emits the following events. An off-chain indexer can subscribe to these to maintain a live view of the publication registry. Event When emitted Fields PublicationCreated New publication created publication: ID , name: String , slug: String PublicationDeleted Publication deleted publication: ID , name: String SlugRegistered Slug claimed in registry slug: String , publication: ID SlugReleased Slug freed on deletion slug: String , publication: ID PublisherCapIssued New publisher cap minted publication: ID , cap: ID PublisherCapRevoked Publisher cap revoked by owner publication: ID , cap: ID CollectionAdded Collection added to publication publication: ID , name: String CollectionRemoved Collection removed from publication publication: ID , name: String"}, {"url": "publications.html#error-codes", "pageTitle": "Publications", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Error Codes", "text": "Code Constant Meaning 6 ESlugAlreadyExists A publication with this slug already exists in the registry 7 ESlugEmpty The provided slug is an empty string 8 ESlugTooLong Slug exceeds 64 characters 9 ESlugInvalidChar Slug contains a character that is not a-z , 0-9 , or - 10 ESlugInvalidEdgeHyphen Slug starts or ends with a hyphen 2 EUnauthorized Capability does not belong to this publication 0 ECollectionAlreadyExists A collection with this name already exists"}, {"url": "collections.html#collections", "pageTitle": "Collections", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Collections", "text": "A collection is a named content lane inside a publication. It groups related entries together and determines how their Walrus payload references are stored."}, {"url": "collections.html#what-is-a-collection", "pageTitle": "Collections", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "What is a Collection?", "text": "Collections organize entries into predictable buckets for editorial workflows and API consumers. A publication holds collections in a VecMap&lt;String, Collection&gt; keyed by name. The choice of VecMap reflects the expectation that a publication will have only a small number of named collections. Move Copy public struct Collection has store { name: String , storage_mode: u8 , // 0 = blob, 1 = quilt  immutable after creation next_entry_id: u64 , // monotonic counter entries: Table &lt; u64 , Entry &gt;, } Entries inside a collection are keyed by a stable monotonic entry_id ( u64 ). IDs are never reused  deletions leave holes in the sequence. This ensures stable external references to individual entries."}, {"url": "collections.html#storage-modes", "pageTitle": "Collections", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Storage Modes", "text": "Every collection has an immutable storage_mode chosen at creation. This controls how entry revisions reference Walrus content. mode 0 Blob Mode Each entry revision references a standalone Walrus Blob object by its Sui object ID. Clean, independent blobs per revision. mode 1 Quilt Mode Each entry revision stores a 37-byte QuiltPatchId pointing to a patch within a shared Walrus Quilt blob."}, {"url": "collections.html#blob-mode-storage-mode-blob-0", "pageTitle": "Collections", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Blob Mode (STORAGE_MODE_BLOB = 0)", "text": "In blob mode, every revision stores a BlobRef::Blob(ID)  the Sui object ID of a standalone Walrus Blob . Each entry revision is fully independent: uploading new content creates a new blob, and the old blobs remain accessible by their IDs. Best for: Articles, blog posts, documentation pages Media libraries (images, videos, audio) Any collection where entries change independently and frequently Situations where you want maximum operational simplicity"}, {"url": "collections.html#quilt-mode-storage-mode-quilt-1", "pageTitle": "Collections", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Quilt Mode (STORAGE_MODE_QUILT = 1)", "text": "In quilt mode, every revision stores a BlobRef::QuiltPatch(vector&lt;u8&gt;)  a 37-byte identifier that locates a patch within a shared Walrus Quilt blob. This is more compact and efficient when updating small parts of a grouped content set. QuiltPatchId layout  37 bytes Copy // Byte layout of a QuiltPatchId: ┌─────────────────────────────────┬─────────┬───────────────┬─────────────┐ │ quilt_blob_id (32 bytes) │ ver (1) │ start_idx (2) │ end_idx (2) │ └─────────────────────────────────┴─────────┴───────────────┴─────────────┘ Walrus blob ID of the quilt version start index end index (this is the Walrus blob_id, (u16 LE) (u16 LE) not the Sui object ID) The contract validates that every QuiltPatchId is exactly 37 bytes. Shorter or longer byte vectors are rejected with EInvalidQuiltPatchId . Best for: Website navigation sections or config-like structured documents Compact content sets updated in place (e.g. featured banners, site metadata) Stable grouped content with targeted patch updates"}, {"url": "collections.html#choosing-a-storage-mode", "pageTitle": "Collections", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Choosing a Storage Mode", "text": "Scenario Recommended mode Growing blog / article feed Blob (0) Frequently updated individual documents Blob (0) Media / asset library Blob (0) Static site sections (header, footer, nav) Quilt (1) Config JSONs updated as a group Quilt (1) Small, bounded content sets Quilt (1) Storage mode is immutable. Once a collection is created with a given storage_mode , it cannot be changed. All entries in the collection must use references that match the mode  the contract enforces this on every write. Choose carefully before creating a collection."}, {"url": "collections.html#creating-a-collection", "pageTitle": "Collections", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Creating a Collection", "text": "Collections are created through the publication module's create_collection function, which requires a valid PublisherCap . The constructor is package-private  external callers always go through the publication API. Move Copy public fun create_collection ( publication: & mut Publication , cap: & PublisherCap , name: String , storage_mode: u8 , // 0 = blob, 1 = quilt ctx: & mut TxContext , ) Collection names must be unique within a publication. Creating a collection with a name that already exists aborts with ECollectionAlreadyExists . Example  creating two collections Copy // Create a blob-mode collection for articles publication:: create_collection ( & mut publication, &publisher_cap, \"articles\" . to_string (), 0 , // STORAGE_MODE_BLOB ctx, ); // Create a quilt-mode collection for site sections publication:: create_collection ( & mut publication, &publisher_cap, \"site-pages\" . to_string (), 1 , // STORAGE_MODE_QUILT ctx, );"}, {"url": "collections.html#deleting-a-collection", "pageTitle": "Collections", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Deleting a Collection", "text": "A collection can be removed from a publication using delete_collection . The collection's entries table must be empty  all entries must be deleted first. Move Copy public fun delete_collection ( publication: & mut Publication , cap: & PublisherCap , name: String , ctx: & mut TxContext , ) Why entries must be removed first. The Table&lt;u64, Entry&gt; that holds entries requires an explicit destroy_empty  Sui's type system does not allow dropping a non-empty table. Delete entries individually with delete_entry_from_collection before removing the collection."}, {"url": "collections.html#entry-ids", "pageTitle": "Collections", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Entry IDs", "text": "When an entry is added to a collection, it is assigned a stable, monotonically increasing entry_id: u64 . The counter starts at 0 and increments with each insertion. Entry IDs are never reused after deletion IDs are stable  external systems can safely hold references by ID Gaps in the ID sequence are expected and normal after deletions Example ID sequence Copy // Add entries: IDs assigned sequentially entry_id = add_entry_to_collection (...) // → 0 entry_id = add_entry_to_collection (...) // → 1 entry_id = add_entry_to_collection (...) // → 2 // Delete entry 1 delete_entry_from_collection (..., entry_id: 1 , ...) // Next add gets ID 3  ID 1 is never reused entry_id = add_entry_to_collection (...) // → 3"}, {"url": "collections.html#error-codes", "pageTitle": "Collections", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Error Codes", "text": "Code Constant Meaning 0 EEntryNotFound No entry exists for the requested entry_id 1 EInvalidStorageMode Storage mode must be 0 or 1"}, {"url": "entries.html#entries-amp-revisions", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Entries &amp; Revisions", "text": "An entry is a single content unit within a collection. Revisions are its immutable history. The dual-head model lets drafts evolve freely while production readers always see a stable published state."}, {"url": "entries.html#entry-structure", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Entry Structure", "text": "Entries live inside collections, stored in a Table&lt;u64, Entry&gt; . They have store and drop abilities  they are values owned by their collection, not independent Sui objects. Move Copy public struct Entry has store , drop { name: String , revisions: vector &lt; EntryRevision &gt;, draft_head: Option &lt; u64 &gt;, // index into revisions public_head: Option &lt; u64 &gt;, // index into revisions }"}, {"url": "entries.html#validation-constraints", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Validation Constraints", "text": "Field Constraint name Non-empty, max 256 characters content_type Non-empty, max 255 characters; standard MIME format recommended"}, {"url": "entries.html#revisions", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Revisions", "text": "Each revision is an immutable snapshot of an entry at a point in time. Revisions are never mutated after creation  edits always append new revisions to the vector. Move Copy public struct EntryRevision has store , drop { blob_ref: BlobRef , // Walrus content reference content_type: String , // MIME type (e.g. \"application/json\") encrypted: bool , access_policy: u8 , // 0=public, 1=publisher, 2=subscription seal_id: Option &lt; vector &lt; u8 &gt;&gt;, // required when encrypted=true author: address , // tx sender at time of write }"}, {"url": "entries.html#the-blobref-enum", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "The BlobRef Enum", "text": "BlobRef is an enum that abstracts the two storage modes: Move Copy public enum BlobRef has copy , drop , store { Blob ( ID ), // Sui object ID of a standalone Walrus Blob QuiltPatch ( vector &lt; u8 &gt;), // 37-byte QuiltPatchId } The variant used must match the collection's storage_mode . The make_blob_ref function enforces this  you cannot accidentally mix modes."}, {"url": "entries.html#the-dual-head-model", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "The Dual-Head Model", "text": "Every entry maintains two independent head pointers into its revision vector: draft_head Points to the latest draft revision. Work in progress  not visible to public readers. May be None on a freshly-published entry. public_head Points to the currently published revision. Stable for readers. May be None on an entry that has only drafts. revisions: [rev0, rev1(draft), rev2(draft), rev3(public), rev4(draft)] &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;↑ public_head=3 &nbsp;&nbsp;↑ draft_head=4 This is what makes real editorial workflows possible: editors can keep appending drafts while production clients continuously serve the stable public_head ."}, {"url": "entries.html#entry-operations", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Entry Operations", "text": ""}, {"url": "entries.html#1-add-an-entry", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "1. Add an Entry", "text": "Create a new entry and add it to a named collection. Returns the assigned entry_id . Move Copy public fun add_entry_to_collection ( publication: & mut Publication , cap: & PublisherCap , collection_name: String , name: String , blob: & Blob , // must be deletable quilt_patch_id: Option &lt; vector &lt; u8 &gt;&gt;, // Some for quilt mode, None for blob mode content_type: String , encrypted: bool , access_policy: u8 , seal_id: Option &lt; vector &lt; u8 &gt;&gt;, ctx: & mut TxContext , ): u64 // returns entry_id For unencrypted public entries: encrypted = false , access_policy = 0 , seal_id = None . The initial revision goes directly to public_head . For encrypted publisher-gated entries: encrypted = true , access_policy = 1 , seal_id = Some(&lt;id&gt;) . The initial revision goes to draft_head ; no public_head yet."}, {"url": "entries.html#2-append-a-draft-revision", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "2. Append a Draft Revision", "text": "Append a new revision to an existing entry and advance draft_head . The previous revisions are untouched. Move Copy public fun append_collection_entry_draft_revision ( publication: & mut Publication , cap: & PublisherCap , collection_name: String , entry_id: u64 , blob: & Blob , quilt_patch_id: Option &lt; vector &lt; u8 &gt;&gt;, content_type: String , encrypted: bool , access_policy: u8 , seal_id: Option &lt; vector &lt; u8 &gt;&gt;, ctx: & mut TxContext , ): u64 // returns new revision_id"}, {"url": "entries.html#3-publish-from-draft", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "3. Publish from Draft", "text": "Take a specific draft revision and publish it  appends a new public (unencrypted, ACCESS_PUBLIC) revision and advances public_head . The draft revision is referenced for traceability. Move Copy public fun publish_collection_entry_from_draft ( publication: & mut Publication , cap: & PublisherCap , collection_name: String , entry_id: u64 , draft_revision_id: u64 , // reference to the specific draft blob: & Blob , quilt_patch_id: Option &lt; vector &lt; u8 &gt;&gt;, content_type: String , ctx: & mut TxContext , ): u64 // returns new revision_id The resulting public revision always has encrypted = false and access_policy = ACCESS_PUBLIC . The publish step always produces a publicly readable revision."}, {"url": "entries.html#4-publish-direct", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "4. Publish Direct", "text": "Skip the draft workflow  append a new public revision directly. For teams with simpler editorial workflows that don't need staging. Move Copy public fun publish_collection_entry_direct ( publication: & mut Publication , cap: & PublisherCap , collection_name: String , entry_id: u64 , blob: & Blob , quilt_patch_id: Option &lt; vector &lt; u8 &gt;&gt;, content_type: String , ctx: & mut TxContext , ): u64"}, {"url": "entries.html#5-delete-an-entry", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "5. Delete an Entry", "text": "Remove an entry by ID. Since Entry has the drop ability, it is simply dropped from the table. Move Copy public fun delete_entry_from_collection ( publication: & mut Publication , cap: & PublisherCap , collection_name: String , entry_id: u64 , ctx: & mut TxContext , ) Blob objects are independent. Deleting an entry removes the on-chain record and the BlobRef , but does not delete the underlying Walrus Blob object on Sui. Blob lifecycle management (storing, deleting the blob object from Walrus) is the caller's responsibility."}, {"url": "entries.html#walrus-blob-requirements", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Walrus Blob Requirements", "text": "All production write paths require a reference to the Walrus &amp;Blob object (not just its ID). The contract calls blob.is_deletable() and aborts with EBlobNotDeletable if the blob is not deletable. This ensures the platform can manage blob lifecycle. Testing without Walrus blobs. In Move unit tests, walrus::blob::Blob cannot be constructed because its constructor is public(package) . Use the _for_testing variants (e.g. add_entry_to_collection_for_testing ) that accept a raw blob_id: ID instead of &amp;Blob . These bypass only the deletable check  all other logic is identical."}, {"url": "entries.html#access-policy-amp-encryption-rules", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Access Policy &amp; Encryption Rules", "text": "The encrypted flag and access_policy must be consistent. The contract enforces this at every write: encrypted access_policy seal_id Result false 0 (PUBLIC) None Valid  unencrypted public revision true 1 (PUBLISHER) Some(&lt;id&gt;) Valid  encrypted publisher-gated revision true 0 any Aborts  EInvalidAccessPolicy false 1 any Aborts  EInvalidAccessPolicy true 1 None Aborts  ESealIdRequired false 0 Some(&lt;id&gt;) Aborts  ESealIdNotAllowed Subscription policy (2) is reserved. ACCESS_SUBSCRIPTION = 2 is defined in the protocol but full end-to-end subscription gating is planned for a future release. The field is validated and stored correctly; the enforcement logic is being built."}, {"url": "entries.html#reading-entry-data", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Reading Entry Data", "text": "The entry module exposes read accessors for the latest revision's data: Move  accessors Copy public fun get_name (entry: & Entry ): String public fun get_draft_head (entry: & Entry ): Option &lt; u64 &gt; public fun get_public_head (entry: & Entry ): Option &lt; u64 &gt; public fun get_blob_ref (entry: & Entry ): BlobRef // from latest revision public fun get_content_type (entry: & Entry ): String public fun get_encrypted (entry: & Entry ): bool public fun get_access_policy (entry: & Entry ): u8 public fun get_seal_id (entry: & Entry ): Option &lt; vector &lt; u8 &gt;&gt; public fun get_author (entry: & Entry ): address // Access a specific revision by index public fun get_revision (entry: & Entry , revision_id: u64 ): & EntryRevision // Access policy constants public fun access_policy_public (): u8 // → 0 public fun access_policy_publisher (): u8 // → 1 public fun access_policy_subscription (): u8 // → 2"}, {"url": "entries.html#typical-editorial-workflow", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Typical Editorial Workflow", "text": "1 Add the entry Call add_entry_to_collection with your Walrus blob. This creates revision 0. For public content, public_head = Some(0) immediately. For encrypted content, draft_head = Some(0) . 2 Iterate in draft Call append_collection_entry_draft_revision as many times as needed. Each call appends a new revision and advances draft_head . Readers still see the old public_head . 3 Publish Call publish_collection_entry_from_draft (referencing a specific draft_revision_id ) or publish_collection_entry_direct . Both append a new public revision and advance public_head . Readers now see the new content. 4 Continue iterating Append more drafts after publishing. The cycle continues without limit. Every revision is preserved in the immutable history vector."}, {"url": "entries.html#error-codes", "pageTitle": "Entries & Revisions", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Error Codes", "text": "Code Constant Meaning 0 ENameEmpty Entry name is empty 1 EContentTypeEmpty Content type is empty 2 ENameTooLong Entry name exceeds 256 characters 3 EContentTypeTooLong Content type exceeds 255 characters 4 ERevisionNotFound Requested revision index does not exist 5 EInvalidAccessPolicy Encrypted/access_policy mismatch 6 ESealIdRequired Encrypted revision must include a Seal identity 7 ESealIdNotAllowed Unencrypted revision must not include a Seal identity 8 EBlobNotDeletable Walrus blob must be deletable 9 EQuiltPatchIdRequired Quilt mode collection requires a QuiltPatchId 10 EQuiltPatchIdNotAllowed Blob mode collection must not include a QuiltPatchId 11 EInvalidQuiltPatchId QuiltPatchId must be exactly 37 bytes"}, {"url": "access-control.html#access-control", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Access Control", "text": "Morse uses a capability-based permission model. Two types of capabilities control who can administer a publication and who can write content  enforced on-chain by the Sui type system, with no off-chain authorization service."}, {"url": "access-control.html#overview", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Overview", "text": "Every write operation in Morse requires presenting a valid capability object. Capabilities cannot be fabricated  they can only be created by the protocol through designated functions. The type system itself is the enforcement mechanism. OwnerCap Admin authority. One per publication. Required to issue and revoke publisher caps, delete the publication, and transfer ownership. has key PublisherCap Write authority. Many per publication. Required for all content operations: create/delete collections and entries. Bound to a specific holder address. has key"}, {"url": "access-control.html#ownercap", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "OwnerCap", "text": "The OwnerCap is the highest-authority object in a publication. Exactly one exists per publication  it is created alongside the publication and transferred to the creator. Move Copy public struct OwnerCap has key { id: UID , publication_id: ID , // which publication this cap administers } Operations that require OwnerCap : issue_publisher_cap  mint a new publisher cap for an address revoke_publisher_cap  add a cap ID to the revocation denylist delete_publication  delete the publication entirely transfer_owner_cap  transfer ownership to a new address OwnerCap is transferable by design. Ownership can be sold, transferred to a multisig wallet, or handed to a DAO treasury. This is a protocol-level feature, not a limitation  publication identity lives in the contract, not in a centralized identity system."}, {"url": "access-control.html#publishercap", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "PublisherCap", "text": "Publisher caps grant write access for daily content operations. Many can exist per publication, issued to different addresses for different editors or automation agents. Move Copy public struct PublisherCap has key { id: UID , publication_id: ID , // scoped to this publication holder: address , // only this address may use this cap } Every write operation that uses a PublisherCap runs three checks internally: Move  internal validation Copy // assert_active_publisher_cap checks all three conditions: assert!(cap.publication_id == object::id(publication), EUnauthorized ); assert!(cap.holder == ctx.sender(), EPublisherCapWrongHolder ); assert!(!revoked_publisher_caps.contains(object::id(cap)), EPublisherCapRevoked ); The holder field is critical: it binds the capability to a specific address. If someone holds the PublisherCap object but the transaction is not signed by holder , the write is rejected. You cannot share a publisher cap between wallets."}, {"url": "access-control.html#issuing-publisher-caps", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Issuing Publisher Caps", "text": "Only the owner can issue publisher caps. The owner calls issue_publisher_cap with the target holder address: Move Copy public fun issue_publisher_cap ( publication: & mut Publication , owner_cap: & OwnerCap , holder: address , ctx: & mut TxContext , ): PublisherCap The returned PublisherCap must then be transferred to holder in the same PTB. No table write occurs during issuance  only revocations write to the denylist. This makes issuing caps essentially free beyond the gas cost of object creation."}, {"url": "access-control.html#revoking-publisher-caps", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Revoking Publisher Caps", "text": "When a publisher needs to be removed, the owner calls revoke_publisher_cap with the cap's object ID: Move Copy public fun revoke_publisher_cap ( publication: & mut Publication , owner_cap: & OwnerCap , cap_id: ID , // object ID of the PublisherCap to revoke ) This adds the cap ID to the revoked_publisher_caps: Table&lt;ID, bool&gt; denylist on the publication. All subsequent writes using that cap will be rejected  the revocation is immediate and requires no cooperation from the cap holder. Double-revoke aborts. Calling revoke_publisher_cap on an already-revoked cap ID aborts with EPublisherCapRevoked . Check the denylist state before revoking if unsure."}, {"url": "access-control.html#the-denylist-model", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "The Denylist Model", "text": "Morse uses a denylist (blocklist), not an allowlist, for publisher cap tracking. This is a deliberate design choice: Denylist (Morse) Allowlist (alternative) Issue cap Zero table writes One table write per issuance Revoke cap One table write One table delete Write validation One table lookup One table lookup Optimized for Common case (no revocations) Frequent churn This is safe because PublisherCap has no store ability and no external constructor  caps cannot be forged outside the module. An attacker cannot create a valid-looking cap; they must obtain a real one from the owner."}, {"url": "access-control.html#destroying-publisher-caps", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Destroying Publisher Caps", "text": "A publisher can voluntarily surrender their write access by calling destroy_publisher_cap : Move Copy public fun destroy_publisher_cap ( publication: & mut Publication , cap: PublisherCap , // consumed ctx: & mut TxContext , ) Only the holder can call this. If the cap was previously revoked, destroy_publisher_cap also removes it from the denylist  cleaning up on-chain storage."}, {"url": "access-control.html#seal-integration", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Seal Integration", "text": "Morse integrates with Seal  Mysten's on-chain access control layer  to gate decryption of encrypted entry payloads. The integration is implemented via an entry fun that Seal calls during the decryption approval flow."}, {"url": "access-control.html#how-it-works", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "How It Works", "text": "When a client wants to decrypt an encrypted Walrus blob, they present a Seal identity to the on-chain approval function: Move Copy // Called by Seal during decryption approval entry fun seal_approve_publisher ( id: vector &lt; u8 &gt;, // Seal identity being approved publication: & Publication , cap: & PublisherCap , ctx: & TxContext , ) The function runs two checks: assert_active_publisher_cap  verifies the cap is valid, not revoked, and the sender is the holder assert_valid_publisher_seal_id  verifies the Seal identity is scoped to this publication and policy"}, {"url": "access-control.html#seal-identity-format", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Seal Identity Format", "text": "Seal identities for Morse follow a structured namespace format to prevent cross-publication identity reuse: Seal ID layout Copy ┌─────────────────────────────────┬────────────────┬──────────────────┐ │ publication_id bytes (32) │ policy_tag (1) │ nonce (variable) │ └─────────────────────────────────┴────────────────┴──────────────────┘ Scopes identity to one Must be 0x01 Differentiates specific publication for publisher multiple identities policy under same namespace The policy_tag = 0x01 is the publisher policy tag. This namespacing ensures: A cap for Publication A cannot approve decryption of Publication B content The same publication can host multiple policy types with different tags in the future (e.g. subscription tag) Many unique Seal identities can exist within one publication namespace (via different nonces)"}, {"url": "access-control.html#error-codes-for-seal", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Error Codes for Seal", "text": "Code Constant Meaning 12 ESealInvalidId Seal identity does not match this publication's namespace 13 ESealWrongPolicyTag Seal identity has an unsupported policy tag byte"}, {"url": "access-control.html#full-authorization-error-codes", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Full Authorization Error Codes", "text": "Code Constant Meaning 2 EUnauthorized Capability does not belong to this publication 4 EPublisherCapWrongHolder Transaction sender is not the cap's bound holder address 5 EPublisherCapRevoked The cap ID is on the revocation denylist"}, {"url": "access-control.html#real-world-usage-pattern", "pageTitle": "Access Control", "section": "Protocol", "heading": "Real-World Usage Pattern", "text": "A concrete example of how a team uses the access control model: 1 Publication created Owner wallet creates the publication. Receives OwnerCap (kept in owner wallet) and an initial PublisherCap (also kept or immediately transferred). 2 Onboard editors For each editor or automation agent, the owner calls issue_publisher_cap(holder: editor_address) and transfers the returned cap to that address. Each cap is independent  revoking one does not affect others. 3 Editors publish content Editors present their PublisherCap in PTBs to create collections, add entries, append drafts, and publish. The contract verifies sender matches holder on every call. 4 Offboard editors When an editor leaves, the owner calls revoke_publisher_cap(cap_id) . The revocation is immediate  the next write attempt using that cap aborts. Historical content is unaffected. 5 Transfer ownership (optional) The owner calls transfer_owner_cap(owner_cap, new_owner_address) . The new owner gains full admin authority immediately. The old owner retains only their PublisherCap (if any) unless it is revoked by the new owner."}, {"url": "contracts.html#contract-reference", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "Contract Reference", "text": "Complete reference for the Morse Move package  modules, public functions, events, error codes, and deployment information."}, {"url": "contracts.html#package", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "Package", "text": "Move.toml Copy name = \"publication\" edition = \"2024\" [dependencies] Sui = { git = \"https://github.com/MystenLabs/sui\" , ... } Walrus = { git = \"https://github.com/MystenLabs/walrus\" , ... } The package name is publication . All three modules live within it: Module Path Responsibility publication::publication sources/publication.move Top-level API: publications, capabilities, collection and entry operations, Seal integration publication::collection sources/collection.move Collection struct, storage modes, entry table management publication::entry sources/entry.move Entry and revision structs, BlobRef enum, validation logic Deployment addresses. Testnet deployment addresses are stored in morse-contracts/Published.toml (committed). Ephemeral localnet addresses go to Pub.local.toml (gitignored). Check the repository for the latest published addresses."}, {"url": "contracts.html#shared-objects", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "Shared Objects", "text": "Two objects are shared at the protocol level  they must be passed as arguments to relevant transactions: Object Created by Required for PublicationRegistry init() at publish time new_publication , delete_publication Publication new_publication + share_publication All collection and entry operations, cap management, Seal"}, {"url": "contracts.html#public-functions", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "Public Functions", "text": ""}, {"url": "contracts.html#publication-publication", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "publication::publication", "text": "Function Required cap Returns Description new_publication(registry, ctx, name, slug)  (Publication, OwnerCap, PublisherCap) Create a new publication. Register slug in registry. share_publication(publication)   Share the publication object so others can interact with it. delete_publication(registry, publication, owner_cap) OwnerCap  Delete publication and release slug. Collections must be empty. transfer_owner_cap(owner_cap, recipient)   Transfer ownership to another address. issue_publisher_cap(publication, owner_cap, holder, ctx) OwnerCap PublisherCap Mint a new publisher cap bound to holder . revoke_publisher_cap(publication, owner_cap, cap_id) OwnerCap  Add cap ID to the revocation denylist. destroy_publisher_cap(publication, cap, ctx) PublisherCap (holder)  Voluntarily surrender write access. Cleans up denylist entry if revoked. create_collection(publication, cap, name, storage_mode, ctx) PublisherCap  Add a new named collection to the publication. delete_collection(publication, cap, name, ctx) PublisherCap  Remove and destroy a collection. Entries must be empty first. add_entry_to_collection(publication, cap, collection_name, name, blob, quilt_patch_id, content_type, encrypted, access_policy, seal_id, ctx) PublisherCap u64 (entry_id) Create a new entry in a named collection. delete_entry_from_collection(publication, cap, collection_name, entry_id, ctx) PublisherCap  Remove an entry by ID. append_collection_entry_draft_revision(publication, cap, collection_name, entry_id, blob, quilt_patch_id, content_type, encrypted, access_policy, seal_id, ctx) PublisherCap u64 (revision_id) Append a draft revision and advance draft_head. publish_collection_entry_from_draft(publication, cap, collection_name, entry_id, draft_revision_id, blob, quilt_patch_id, content_type, ctx) PublisherCap u64 (revision_id) Publish from a draft  appends public revision, advances public_head. publish_collection_entry_direct(publication, cap, collection_name, entry_id, blob, quilt_patch_id, content_type, ctx) PublisherCap u64 (revision_id) Publish directly without a draft step. contains_slug(registry, slug)  bool Check if a slug is currently registered. get_publication_id_by_slug(registry, slug)  &amp;ID Resolve a slug to its publication's object ID."}, {"url": "contracts.html#entry-fun-seal", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "entry fun  Seal", "text": "Function Description seal_approve_publisher(id, publication, cap, ctx) Called by Seal during decryption approval. Validates active publisher cap and correct Seal identity namespace."}, {"url": "contracts.html#publication-collection-public", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "publication::collection (public)", "text": "Function Returns Description get_name(collection) String Return the collection's display name. get_storage_mode(collection) u8 Return the storage mode constant (0 or 1). entries_length(collection) u64 Return the number of entries currently in the collection."}, {"url": "contracts.html#publication-entry-public", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "publication::entry (public)", "text": "Function Returns Description get_name(entry) String Entry display name. get_draft_head(entry) Option&lt;u64&gt; Current draft revision index. get_public_head(entry) Option&lt;u64&gt; Current public revision index. get_blob_ref(entry) BlobRef BlobRef from the latest revision. get_content_type(entry) String MIME content type from latest revision. get_encrypted(entry) bool Whether the latest revision is encrypted. get_access_policy(entry) u8 Access policy from the latest revision. get_seal_id(entry) Option&lt;vector&lt;u8&gt;&gt; Seal identity from the latest revision. get_author(entry) address Author address from the latest revision. get_revision(entry, revision_id) &amp;EntryRevision Access a specific revision by index. access_policy_public() u8 (0) The ACCESS_PUBLIC constant. access_policy_publisher() u8 (1) The ACCESS_PUBLISHER constant. access_policy_subscription() u8 (2) The ACCESS_SUBSCRIPTION constant."}, {"url": "contracts.html#events", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "Events", "text": "All events have copy, drop abilities and are emitted from publication::publication . Event Fields Trigger PublicationCreated publication: ID , name: String , slug: String new_publication PublicationDeleted publication: ID , name: String delete_publication SlugRegistered slug: String , publication: ID Slug claimed in registry (always emitted with PublicationCreated ) SlugReleased slug: String , publication: ID Slug freed from registry (always emitted with PublicationDeleted ) PublisherCapIssued publication: ID , cap: ID issue_publisher_cap PublisherCapRevoked publication: ID , cap: ID revoke_publisher_cap CollectionAdded publication: ID , name: String create_collection CollectionRemoved publication: ID , name: String delete_collection"}, {"url": "contracts.html#complete-error-code-reference", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "Complete Error Code Reference", "text": ""}, {"url": "contracts.html#publication-publication", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "publication::publication", "text": "Code Constant Module section Meaning 0 ECollectionAlreadyExists Collections Collection with this name already exists 2 EUnauthorized Authorization Capability does not belong to this publication 4 EPublisherCapWrongHolder Authorization Sender is not the cap's bound holder 5 EPublisherCapRevoked Authorization Cap ID is on the revocation denylist 6 ESlugAlreadyExists Registry Slug is already registered 7 ESlugEmpty Registry Slug is empty 8 ESlugTooLong Registry Slug exceeds 64 characters 9 ESlugInvalidChar Registry Slug contains invalid characters 10 ESlugInvalidEdgeHyphen Registry Slug starts or ends with hyphen 12 ESealInvalidId Seal Seal identity doesn't match publication namespace 13 ESealWrongPolicyTag Seal Seal identity has unsupported policy tag"}, {"url": "contracts.html#publication-collection", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "publication::collection", "text": "Code Constant Meaning 0 EEntryNotFound No entry exists for the requested entry_id 1 EInvalidStorageMode Storage mode must be 0 or 1"}, {"url": "contracts.html#publication-entry", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "publication::entry", "text": "Code Constant Meaning 0 ENameEmpty Entry name is empty 1 EContentTypeEmpty Content type is empty 2 ENameTooLong Entry name exceeds 256 characters 3 EContentTypeTooLong Content type exceeds 255 characters 4 ERevisionNotFound Requested revision index out of bounds 5 EInvalidAccessPolicy Encryption/access_policy mismatch 6 ESealIdRequired Encrypted revisions require a Seal identity 7 ESealIdNotAllowed Unencrypted revisions must not include a Seal identity 8 EBlobNotDeletable Walrus blob must be deletable 9 EQuiltPatchIdRequired Quilt mode collection requires a QuiltPatchId 10 EQuiltPatchIdNotAllowed Blob mode collection must not include a QuiltPatchId 11 EInvalidQuiltPatchId QuiltPatchId must be exactly 37 bytes"}, {"url": "contracts.html#constants", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "Constants", "text": "Module Constant Value Meaning publication MAX_SLUG_LENGTH 64 Maximum slug length in bytes entry MAX_ENTRY_NAME_LENGTH 256 Maximum entry name length in bytes entry MAX_CONTENT_TYPE_LENGTH 255 Maximum content_type length in bytes entry QUILT_PATCH_ID_LENGTH 37 Required exact byte length of QuiltPatchId entry ACCESS_PUBLIC 0 Unencrypted public access policy entry ACCESS_PUBLISHER 1 Publisher-gated encrypted access policy entry ACCESS_SUBSCRIPTION 2 Subscription-gated access policy (reserved) publication SEAL_POLICY_TAG_PUBLISHER 0x01 Seal identity policy tag for publisher gating collection STORAGE_MODE_BLOB 0 Standalone Walrus Blob storage mode collection STORAGE_MODE_QUILT 1 QuiltPatch-addressed storage mode"}, {"url": "contracts.html#object-abilities", "pageTitle": "Contract Reference", "section": "Smart Contracts", "heading": "Object Abilities", "text": "Type Abilities Notes Publication key Shared object. No store  prevents wrapping. PublicationRegistry key Shared singleton. Created in init() . OwnerCap key Owned object. Transferable. One per publication. PublisherCap key Owned object. Holder-bound. Many per publication. Collection store Wrapped value inside Publication.collections . Entry store, drop Wrapped value inside Collection.entries . EntryRevision store, drop Value in Entry.revisions vector. BlobRef copy, drop, store Enum  either Blob(ID) or QuiltPatch(vector&lt;u8&gt;) ."}, {"url": "glossary.html#glossary", "pageTitle": "Glossary", "section": "Reference", "heading": "Glossary", "text": "Terms used throughout the Morse protocol and this documentation."}, {"url": "glossary.html#a", "pageTitle": "Glossary", "section": "Reference", "heading": "A", "text": "Access Policy A numeric constant stored per revision that defines who can read the payload. Current values: 0 (public), 1 (publisher), 2 (subscription, reserved). Enforced in combination with the encrypted flag. Agent-first A design principle in Morse meaning the protocol is usable by autonomous coding agents through CLI/SDK/contract interfaces without requiring human-in-the-loop authorization or provisioning steps."}, {"url": "glossary.html#b", "pageTitle": "Glossary", "section": "Reference", "heading": "B", "text": "Blob Mode Storage mode 0 for collections. Each entry revision stores a BlobRef::Blob(ID) pointing to an independent Walrus Blob object by Sui object ID. Best for growing, frequently-changing collections. See Collections . BlobRef A Move enum stored per revision that abstracts the two Walrus payload reference formats. Variants: Blob(ID) for standalone blobs, QuiltPatch(vector&lt;u8&gt;) for 37-byte quilt patch identifiers."}, {"url": "glossary.html#c", "pageTitle": "Glossary", "section": "Reference", "heading": "C", "text": "Capability A Move object that proves authorization to perform a specific action. Morse has two capability types: OwnerCap (admin authority) and PublisherCap (write authority). Capabilities cannot be fabricated  they can only be issued by the protocol. CMS Content Management System. Software for creating, organizing, and publishing structured digital content. Morse implements a decentralized, headless CMS protocol where permission management lives on-chain rather than in a centralized backend. Collection A named content lane inside a publication . Holds entries in a table keyed by monotonic entry_id values. Has an immutable storage_mode (blob or quilt). See Collections . Content Type A MIME-format string stored per entry revision that describes the payload format (e.g. application/json , text/markdown , image/png ). Max 255 characters. Lowercase is recommended for consistency but not enforced on-chain."}, {"url": "glossary.html#d", "pageTitle": "Glossary", "section": "Reference", "heading": "D", "text": "dCMS Decentralized Content Management System  the category Morse belongs to. Publication identity, authorization, and state transitions are governed on-chain; payloads are stored off-chain in decentralized storage (Walrus). Denylist The revocation model used for PublisherCap s. A Table&lt;ID, bool&gt; on each publication stores IDs of revoked caps. Issuance writes nothing to the table; only revocations write. This optimizes for the common case where revocations never occur. Draft Head An Option&lt;u64&gt; pointer in an Entry that tracks the index of the latest draft revision. May be None if no draft has been created. Updated by append_collection_entry_draft_revision . Dual-head Model The entry versioning architecture where each entry maintains two independent revision head pointers: draft_head (latest work-in-progress) and public_head (currently published). Enables editorial iteration without disrupting stable reader delivery."}, {"url": "glossary.html#e", "pageTitle": "Glossary", "section": "Reference", "heading": "E", "text": "Entry A single content unit within a collection. Holds a name, an immutable revision vector, and two head pointers. Identified by a stable monotonic entry_id within its collection. See Entries &amp; Revisions . Entry ID A u64 assigned to an entry when added to a collection. Values start at 0 and increment monotonically. IDs are never reused after deletion  stable for external references."}, {"url": "glossary.html#h", "pageTitle": "Glossary", "section": "Reference", "heading": "H", "text": "Headless CMS A CMS architecture that separates content management from presentation. The CMS manages content and metadata; client applications decide how to render it. Content is delivered through APIs. Morse follows this model while decentralizing identity, authorization, and state transitions. Holder The address field on a PublisherCap that binds the capability to a specific wallet. Write operations check that tx.sender() == cap.holder . A cap cannot be shared between addresses."}, {"url": "glossary.html#o", "pageTitle": "Glossary", "section": "Reference", "heading": "O", "text": "OwnerCap The admin capability for a publication. Exactly one exists per publication. Grants authority to issue and revoke publisher caps, delete the publication, and transfer ownership. Has key ability only  transferable via transfer_owner_cap . See Access Control ."}, {"url": "glossary.html#p", "pageTitle": "Glossary", "section": "Reference", "heading": "P", "text": "Publication The top-level Morse content domain. A shared Sui object that bundles a name, an immutable slug, named collections, and a revocation denylist. Created via new_publication . See Publications . PublicationRegistry A shared singleton Sui object created at package deploy time. Maintains a Table&lt;String, ID&gt; that maps slugs to publication IDs, enforcing global slug uniqueness. Required argument for new_publication and delete_publication . Public Head An Option&lt;u64&gt; pointer in an Entry that tracks the index of the currently published revision. What reader-facing clients should read. Updated by publish_collection_entry_from_draft and publish_collection_entry_direct . PublisherCap The write capability for a publication. Many can exist per publication. Grants authority to create/delete collections and entries, append drafts, and publish content. Bound to a holder address. Issued by the owner; revocable by the owner. See Access Control . PTB Programmable Transaction Block  Sui's composable transaction format. Multiple operations can be combined into a single atomic transaction. The Morse protocol uses pure creation functions that return objects for callers to compose in PTBs."}, {"url": "glossary.html#q", "pageTitle": "Glossary", "section": "Reference", "heading": "Q", "text": "Quilt Mode Storage mode 1 for collections. Each entry revision stores a 37-byte QuiltPatchId pointing to a patch within a shared Walrus Quilt blob. Best for stable, grouped content sets. See Collections . QuiltPatchId A 37-byte identifier used in quilt mode collections. Layout: quilt_blob_id (32 bytes) || version (1 byte) || start_index (2 bytes) || end_index (2 bytes) . Stored as a BlobRef::QuiltPatch(vector&lt;u8&gt;) ."}, {"url": "glossary.html#r", "pageTitle": "Glossary", "section": "Reference", "heading": "R", "text": "Revision An immutable version of an entry at a point in time. Stored in the entry's revisions: vector&lt;EntryRevision&gt; . Each revision records a BlobRef , content type, encryption state, access policy, optional Seal identity, and author address. Revisions are never mutated  edits append new ones. See Entries &amp; Revisions . Revision ID The index of a revision within an entry's revisions vector. Starts at 0 . Returned by all revision-appending functions. Used to reference a specific revision in publish_collection_entry_from_draft . Revocation The act of adding a PublisherCap 's object ID to a publication's denylist via revoke_publisher_cap . Immediate effect  the next write attempt using the revoked cap will abort. Historical content is unaffected."}, {"url": "glossary.html#s", "pageTitle": "Glossary", "section": "Reference", "heading": "S", "text": "Seal Mysten Labs' on-chain access control layer for Walrus blob decryption. Morse integrates via the seal_approve_publisher entry function, which validates that a publisher cap holder can decrypt a specific encrypted payload. Seal Identity A byte vector ( vector&lt;u8&gt; ) that Seal presents to the approval function during decryption. In Morse, the format is: [publication_id (32 bytes)][policy_tag (1 byte)][nonce (variable)] . Scopes decryption approval to a specific publication and policy. Slug A short, unique identifier for a publication . Immutable after creation. Constraints: lowercase a-z , digits 0-9 , hyphens; max 64 characters; no leading/trailing hyphens. Enforced globally by the PublicationRegistry . Storage Mode An immutable property of a collection that determines how entry revision blob references are stored. 0 = blob mode (standalone Walrus blobs), 1 = quilt mode (QuiltPatchId references). Sui The Layer 1 blockchain on which Morse contracts are deployed. Sui uses the Move programming language and features an object-centric data model, parallel execution, and programmable transaction blocks."}, {"url": "glossary.html#w", "pageTitle": "Glossary", "section": "Reference", "heading": "W", "text": "Walrus MystenLabs' decentralized blob storage network integrated with Sui. Morse stores all content payloads in Walrus  the contracts hold references ( BlobRef ), not the raw bytes. Walrus is format-agnostic; payload interpretation is the client's responsibility. Walrus Blob A Sui object ( walrus::blob::Blob ) representing a payload stored in the Walrus network. Production Morse write paths require a reference to this object (not just the blob ID) so the contract can verify the blob is deletable."}];
